<!--
  Tells the trimmer about the one thing it cannot see in this library.

  Every wrapper is built by the marshaller graph through Activator.CreateInstance(type, jsRef) - see
  SpawnJSObjectMarshaller.JSToNet. Nothing ever calls those constructors statically, so the trimmer
  removes them and the first marshal of a wrapper fails at runtime with
  "MissingMethodException: MissingConstructor_Name, SpawnDev.SpawnJS.JSObjects.Error".

  preserve="methods" covers the constructor AND the property accessors. The accessors matter because
  ObjectMarshaller and StructMarshaller walk a type's members and call PropertyInfo.GetValue/SetValue,
  which nothing calls statically either - so a marshalled descriptor POCO whose getters were trimmed
  fails at runtime with "ArgumentException: Arg_GetMethNotFnd" the first time it is written to
  Javascript. Only a TRIMMED test run shows this; an untrimmed suite is green either way.

  required="false" is the important part: it does NOT root these types. A wrapper the app never mentions
  is still removed entirely. This only says that IF a type is kept, its members are kept with it - which
  is exactly the guarantee the marshaller needs.

  Measured cost of preserving methods rather than just the constructor: WasmBrowserDemo, which runs the
  whole test suite and so touches far more of the library than a real app, went 1017 KB -> 1101 KB.
  WasmConsoleDemo was unchanged at 136 KB. The trimmed console suite goes from 5 failures to 0.

  Shipped as an embedded resource so it travels in the package. An app consuming SpawnDev.SpawnJS can
  turn on PublishTrimmed without knowing any of this exists.
-->
<linker>
  <assembly fullname="SpawnDev.SpawnJS">
    <type fullname="SpawnDev.SpawnJS.JSObjects*" required="false" preserve="methods" />
    <type fullname="SpawnDev.SpawnJS.SpawnJSObject" required="false">
      <method signature="System.Void .ctor(SpawnDev.SpawnJS.SpawnJSObjectReference)" />
    </type>
  </assembly>
</linker>
